                  </persName>
            , of Highgate, amounting altogether to 10,000 l. 5 per cent. were produced and shewn to him. I think only the transfer book was produced. The Governor, Deputy-Governor, Chief Cashier, and myself were altogether. The prisoner was sent for by Foy, the police officer; he came there about five o'clock, he was not at the Bank at the time the irregularities were discovered. He was sent for about three o'clock, Norris and Foy went for him to his house at Walworth. The first transfer that was turned to after he came into the Governor's room was that of the 21st of March, 1821; to Mr. Starling for 1000 l. On turning to it I asked<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182109120034"></xptr>him who Mr. J. Smith was, by whom the name of 
               <persName id="t18210912-64-person687">
                  John 
                  Penn
